        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2"><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote><BR>^2^Plant 1: Any of the great group of living things (as mushrooms, seaweeds, or trees) that usu. have no locomotor ability or obvious sense organs and have cellulose cell walls and usu. capacity for indefenite growth.<BR><hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>Technically, including mushrooms in this list is wrong.  Mushrooms, and other fungi, don't have cellulose cell walls, they have chitin cell walls.  Scientifically, Fungi and Plants are 2 totally different things.  Fungi also have no chlorophyll, and this is why they can grow without sunlight (plants die without light).  Calling fungi plants simply because they cannot move is no more accurate than calling an amoeba an animal because they both can.</P><P>However, all that being said, I highly doubt Verant knows or thought about this before implementing the spell, and as far as they SHOULD be concerned, the defoliation spell should work on all plant-LIKE organisms, to include treants, fungi-men, cacti that shuffle about, and even the lowly muchroom.  They key here is consistancy, a spell should either work on all of a given type of thing, or none of it.  Unfortunately, even our undead line works this way too, one skeletal creature you meet might be undead, but the one that looks exactly like it and is standing right next to it is not.  Or to put it simply, it's all fucked up.</P><P><IMG src="http://neverquest.homestead.com/files/OurMoon/OurMoon.jpg"><BR><i>"Verant celebrates the success of their latest expansion."<i></P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
